This was one of the best courses I took in my entire undergrad. Prof Bilton is awesome and encourages lots of class discussion. Draws on her own experience and goes above and beyond for the students.
Good balance of workload and difficulty. Slotine/Lee Great textbook. Very available to advise after class/office hours

rComments: Prof Bilton is one of the best profs I've had in my entire undergrad.  She genuinely cares for her students and tries to make the classes engaging.  Would take her classes again for sure.

One of the best profs I've had in my undergrad at U of T. Her classes are engaging and she spends a lot of time preparing the material. Happily takes questions in and out of class. Definitely a hard marker, but I've learned a great amount in her class!
She cannot teach concepts well, rushes, and people pleaser. Demands too much in too little time. Cannot help when it gets difficult.

Prof Bilton is a great person. She genuinely cares and tries to get to know her students, even in large classes. She doesn't give out free grades like some profs here (so maybe that's why her rating here isn't that high), but she is easily one of the most approachable people in the faculty.
Is helpful and approachable, but course is tough.

Knows the material, but lectures aren't engaging at all. Disorganized, tries to rush through teaching concepts when behind. Needs to understand how to progressively develop concepts. Focus on examples in class is weak.   Teacher's college recommended.
Goes out of way to help students when asked.  Tests are tough.
She is the type of professor to start a new chapter on the last lecture and include it on the exam.
I would avoid her if possible. Lectures leave you lost and confused and her notes taking style was not good.
Is helpful and approachable. Has high expectations which reflects itself in the way she marks and difficulty of material.
